ctionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","from the Middle English personal name <i>Hewet</i>, <i>Huet</i>, <i>Hughet</i>, <i>Howet</i>, pet forms of <i>Hugh</i> (Middle English <i>Hewe</i>, <i>Hue</i>; see   Hugh   and compare   Hew  ). The spelling <i>Hughet</i> stood for both <i>Huet</i> and the synonymous <i>Huget</i>; see   Huggett  . This surname has also been established in Ireland since the 14th century.","habitational name from Hewitts in Chelsfield or Hewitts in Willesborough (both Kent), both named from Old English <i>hīewett</i> ‘cutting’, denoting a place where trees had been cut down. Here there lived families called <i>de la Hewatte</i> (1270), <i>de la hewett</i> (1301), and <i>atte Hewete</i> (1338). The name may also be topographic for someone who lived in a newly made clearing in a wood."],"variants":[{"name":"Howatt","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Hewitt  ."]},{"name":"Hewatt","meanings":["English: variant of   Hewitt  ."]},{"name":"Hewitson","meanings":["English (northern): patronymic from the personal name <i>Hewet</i>; see   Hewitt  ."]},{"name":"Howett","meanings":["English (East Midlands): variant of   Hewitt  ."]},{"name":"Huett","meanings":["English (Somerset): variant of   Hewitt  .","German (<b>Hütt</b>): status name for someone living in a hut or owning a small shop, Middle High German <i>hütte</i>, or a habitational name from any of several places called Hütt or Hütte. Compare   Hutt  ."]},{"name":"Hewett","meanings":["English: variant of   Hewitt  ."]},{"name":"Howat","meanings":["Scottish (southwestern): variant of   Hewitt  ."]},{"name":"Howitt","meanings":["English (East Midlands): variant of   Hewitt  ."]},{"name":"Hugh","meanings":["English, Welsh, and Scottish (of Norman origin): from the Old French personal name <i>Hue</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Hugo</i> (ultimately derived from <i>hugi-</i> ‘mind, spirit’). This was a very popular name in England after the Norman Conquest, partly due to the reputation of Saint Hugh of Lincoln (1140–1200), who was born in Burgundy and who established the first Carthusian monastery in England.","Scottish and Irish: adopted as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic personal name <i>Aodh</i>, a derivative of a Gaelic word meaning ‘fire’. See   Hughes  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surnames 邱 and 丘, based on their Hakka pronunciation; see   Qiu   1 and 2."]},{"name":"Huet","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Andre.","English: variant of   Hewitt  .","French: from a pet form of the personal name   Hue   ‘Hugh’."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":27,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Elizabeth Hewitt was born in 1355, in Baddington, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, John Hewitt, was 34 and her mother, Catherine Bowles, was 27. She married Richard de Hexstall I about 1381, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1382, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 27."},"et":{"1355–1382":"1355–1382","1365–1382":"1365–1382","1350–1382":"1350–1382","1382–1410":"1382–1410","1321–1385":"1321–1385","1328–1385":"1328–1385","1348":"1348","abt.  1381":"umbes 1381","1355":"1355","1410":"1410","1365":"1365","1321":"1321","1385":"1385","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1328":"1328","Baddington, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Baddington, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Walsall, Stafordshire, England":"Walsall, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Baddington, Cheshire, England":"Baddington, Cheshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hexstall's Court, East Peckham, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"East Peckham, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1355–1382":"1355–1382","1365–1382":"1365–1382","1350–1382":"1350–1382","1382–1410":"1382–1410","1321–1385":"1321–1385","1328–1385":"1328–1385","1348":"1348","abt.  1381":"noin 1381","1355":"1355","1410":"1410","1365":"1365","1321":"1321","1385":"1385","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1328":"1328","Baddington, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Baddington, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Walsall, Stafordshire, England":"Walsall, 